Module 64
📘 Legal Calculus 4.5
Tier 6 — Procedural Sovereignty
Module 64 – Notice Architecture: Redundant Paths, Single Story 🔔🧱
⚖️ Core Message
Notice is fragile if it’s single‑threaded. Design redundant paths (mail, portal, email) that tell one consistent story in the record.

📖 Lesson Content
• Three‑Channel Rule — Portal receipt + certified mail + email confirmation when allowed.
• Consistent Slugs — Same filename slug and caption across channels.
• Declaration Tie‑In — One declaration describing all notice events with timestamps.
• Index — Notice Index page that lists each channel for each filing.
• QC — Spot‑check for divergent versions; hash the final PDF.
📝 Assignment
Create a Notice Index template (table) and fill it for the last three filings you made.

✅ Model Answer (Template)
NOTICE INDEX ROW
Filing: TRO pkg; Portal: Rec#8472 (Ex. A); Mail: 7011… (Ex. B); Email: 08/10 18:05 (Ex. C).

💡 Reflection
Redundancy prevents selective amnesia.

🎨 Visual Pairing
Three arrows (portal/mail/email) converging into one 'Notice Index' tile.



Legal Calculus 4.5 Advanced — Tier 6 | Page of
Module 65
📘 Legal Calculus 4.5
Tier 6 — Procedural Sovereignty
Module 65 – Version Control for Law: Hash, Bates, and Changelog 🧾🔐
⚖️ Core Message
Procedural sovereignty requires a single source of truth. Hash your PDFs, Bates your exhibits, and keep a changelog that explains edits.

📖 Lesson Content
• Hashes — SHA‑256 for exhibits; list values in briefs and ledgers.
• Bates — LC0001… LC0020; cite pin‑pages consistently.
• Changelog — Date, file, change, reason; version tags (v1.1.0).
• Public vs Restricted — Mirror redacted versions; keep originals immutable.
• Tooling — Script or manual; either beats memory.
📝 Assignment
Produce a one‑page changelog and hash manifest for your last motion + exhibits (A–C).

✅ Model Answer (Template)
CHANGELOG
2025‑09‑02: Ex. B redacted phone number; v1.1.1; reason: PII.

💡 Reflection
Trust follows consistency; consistency follows a process.

🎨 Visual Pairing
A document stamped with 'HASH' and 'LC0001' labels, next to a small 'changelog.txt'.



