Module 81
📘 Legal Calculus 4.5
Tier 6 — Procedural Sovereignty
Module 81 – Protective Orders & Sealing: Public Where Possible, Private Where Necessary 🔏⚖️
⚖️ Core Message
Default to openness; seal only what’s necessary. When sealing, describe narrowly and offer a public‑redacted version.

📖 Lesson Content
• Standards — Show compelling reasons or good cause; cite local rule.
• Narrow — Redact specific lines; avoid blanket sealing.
• Public Version — File a redacted PDF; mark '[REDACTED]' clearly.
• Lifecycle — Revisit sealing after milestones; unseal if risk passes.
• Index — Keep a sealed/redacted index with reasons.
📝 Assignment
Draft a Motion to Seal (or Protective Order) with a redaction log and a public‑redacted exhibit version.

✅ Model Answer (Template)
MOTION TO SEAL (EXCERPT)
Good cause exists to redact PII at Ex. B p.2 line 7 (phone number); redacted version filed as Ex. B‑R.

💡 Reflection
Transparency builds trust; careful sealing protects people.

🎨 Visual Pairing
A padlock icon over a document with black bars and a small '[REDACTED]' tag.



